<article>
    <h1>New smart flats a good way to foster greener life&#xAD;style</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201013/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-13"><time>2020-10-13</time></a>
        - <span>FORUM</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>It is en­cour­ag­ing to see con­crete steps be­ing taken to­wards ful­fill­ing Sin­ga­pore’s goal of be­com­ing a smart city (First batch of HDB smart homes ready in Pung­gol, Oct 10).</p>
    <p>Hav­ing smart-en­abled homes is so much more than just a nov­elty. It em­pow­ers the com­mu­nity and gives us the abil­ity to bet­ter tackle is­sues plagu­ing our en­vi­ron­ment.</p>
    <p>It pro­vides the tools to com­bat is­sues that we of­ten find our­selves ranked poorly for, like house­hold waste man­age­ment and sav­ing water or elec­tric­ity.</p>
    <p>Now that we are mov­ing to­wards equip­ping our­selves with the tech­nol­ogy, the com­mu­nity needs to put in more work to­wards making full use of it. I hope that the smart-en­abled Hous­ing Board flats in Pung­gol Northshore will have some schemes or pro­grammes to en­cour­age house­holds to mon­i­tor their waste, re­cy­cle more, as well as be­come more con­scious of their use of util­i­ties. Such schemes could be ex­per­i­mented with on these new blocks be­fore be­ing ex­tended na­tion­wide.</p>
    <p>Change is never easy, but we have to start some­where.</p>
    <p>Jor­dan Leong Wei</p>


</article>

